Fixed by doing paranoid null checks for plugin IDs.

It seems that you have a plug-in project in your workspace that has no symbolic name (ie. id), which is causing the problem here.  Or it could be that you have a plug-in whose manifest.mf could not be read properly.

Hello, 

We are working w/RC6 right now on my current project, we are not ready to migrate to RC2 just yet.  I am running into this problem and I have gone through all the plugins and they all seem to have the ID set properly.  

The message in the error log does not seem to indicate to me exactly which plugin is misconfigured; is there a way that I can determine if a Manifest file is not able to be read properly, or should I just debug the workbench?

Thanks in advance

John, your host version does not necessarily have to be the same as your target.

So you can use 3.2RC4 as your host, and your target can be your M6-based product.

As for figuring out what plugin is the culprit, it would have to be by trial and error then.
